In[13]:
# Mapping 2-letter codes to full country names
country_dict = {
    "US": "United States",
    "GB": "United Kingdom",
    "CA": "Canada",
    "DE": "Germany",
    "IN": "India",
    "FR": "France",
    "ES": "Spain",
    "GR": "Greece",
    "JP": "Japan",
    "NL": "Netherlands"
}

# Create a new column with full country names
df["company_country"] = df["company_location"].map(country_dict)
In[14]:

    hover_name="job_title",
    title="Top Data Science Jobs Around the World"
)

fig.show()

import plotly.figure_factory as ff

heat_data = df.pivot_table(
    index="experience_level",
    columns="job_title",
    values="salary_in_usd",
    aggfunc="mean"
).fillna(0)

fig = px.imshow(
    heat_data,
    text_auto=True,
    aspect="auto",
    title="Average Salary by Job Title and Experience Level"
)
fig.show()

In[20]:
import plotly.graph_objects as go

top_jobs = df['job_title'].value_counts().head(3).index
categories = list(df['experience_level'].unique())

fig = go.Figure()

for job in top_jobs:
    values = []
    for exp in categories:
        avg_salary = df[(df['job_title']==job) & (df['experience_level']==exp)]['salary_in_usd'].mean()
        values.append(avg_salary)
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatterpolar(
        r=values,
        theta=categories,
        fill='toself',
        name=job
    ))

fig.update_layout(
    polar=dict(radialaxis=dict(visible=True)),
    title="Average Salary by Experience Level for Top Job Roles"
)
fig.show()
